<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-798-992  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 798 992.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 23 1989 v23 n43 p80(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The hacker as scapegoat. (Steven Levy on MIS's unjustified fear ofcomputer hackers) (includes an excerpt from William Gibson'sscience-fiction novel Neuromancer) (Executive Report: Security inOpen Times) (interview)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Steven Levy, author of the book 'Hackers', discusses the evolutionof what is called hackerism and the exaggerated threat it poses tocorporate information systems.andP;  Levy defines a hacker as someonewith a near total devotion to computers and who has a strongdesire to do the impossible.andP;  Hackers also have an insatiablequest for information and knowledge on a range of subjects, notjust on computers.andP;  It is unfair to think of a hacker as acriminal, Levy claims, although most hackers admire awell-engineered incursion into a computer system.andP;  Levy definesthe term 'cyberpunk' as a genre of science fiction writing thatdeals with disenfranchised youth who take to computer hacking,although it also can refer to hackers who take a nihilisticapproach to computing.andP;  Levy also discusses the threat of computerviruses and hackers in general to MIS and the fiction of WilliamGibson.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data SecurityMISPlanningNetwork Access ProceduresComputer hackersComputer viruses.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Steven Levy. (portrait)Person:    Levy, Steven (interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>